‚úÖ Complete Networking Guide (Basics ‚Üí Advanced)
1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Networking?
Networking is the process of connecting two or more devices so they can:

‚úî Share data
‚úî Communicate
‚úî Share hardware (printers, storage)
‚úî Access internet or internal services

Data travels using wired (Ethernet, fiber) or wireless (Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, 5G) technology.

2Ô∏è‚É£ How Networking Works (Step-by-Step)
Networking follows layered architecture. The most important model is:

üîµ OSI Model ‚Äî 7 Layers (Bottom ‚Üí Top)
Layer 1 ‚Äî Physical Layer
What it does:
Transmits raw electrical/optical/radio signals (0s & 1s)

Responsibilities:

Bit transmission

Voltages, modulation

Cable types (UTP, fiber)

Wi-Fi signals

NIC hardware

Devices: Hub, Repeater, Cables, Transceiver

Layer 2 ‚Äî Data Link Layer
What it does:
Moves frames between devices on the same LAN. Uses MAC addresses.

Responsibilities:

Framing

Error detection (CRC)

MAC addressing

Flow control

Switch forwarding

Protocols: Ethernet, PPP, HDLC, Frame Relay
Devices: Switch, Bridge

Outputs: Frames (MAC + Data)

Layer 3 ‚Äî Network Layer
What it does:
Provides routing between networks using IP addresses.

Responsibilities:

Routing

Logical addressing (IPv4/IPv6)

Packet forwarding

Fragmentation

Path selection

Protocols: IPv4, IPv6, ICMP, ARP, OSPF, BGP, RIP
Devices: Router, Layer 3 Switch

Outputs: Packets (IP header + data)

Layer 4 ‚Äî Transport Layer
What it does:
Responsible for end-to-end communication.

Responsibilities:

Segmentation & Reassembly

Ports (HTTP:80, DNS:53, SSH:22)

Reliability (TCP)

Connection-oriented/less

Protocols:

TCP ‚Üí reliable, ordered, slow

UDP ‚Üí fast, connectionless (DNS, streaming)

Outputs: Segments (TCP/UDP + data)

Layer 5 ‚Äî Session Layer
What it does:
Manages sessions/connections between applications.

Responsibilities:

Session creation

Session maintenance

Authentication

Dialog control

Graceful disconnect

Protocols: NetBIOS, RPC, PPTP, NFS

Layer 6 ‚Äî Presentation Layer
What it does:
Formats, encrypts, compresses data.

Responsibilities:

Encryption (SSL/TLS)

Compression

Encoding (JPEG, MP3, MP4)

Serialization (JSON, XML)

Layer 7 ‚Äî Application Layer
What it does:
Provides services directly to user applications.

Examples:

Web browsing ‚Üí HTTP/HTTPS

Email ‚Üí SMTP, IMAP, POP3

File transfer ‚Üí FTP, SFTP

DNS ‚Üí Name resolution

DHCP ‚Üí IP assignment

3Ô∏è‚É£ TCP/IP Model (Real-World Model)
Equivalent of OSI:

OSI Layer	TCP/IP Layer
Application	Application
Presentation	Application
Session	Application
Transport	Transport
Network	Internet
Data Link	Network Access
Physical	Network Access
4Ô∏è‚É£ Data Flow ‚Äî Encapsulation & Decapsulation
Sender Side ‚Äî Encapsulation
Application Layer ‚Üí Adds application header

Transport Layer ‚Üí Adds TCP/UDP header

Network Layer ‚Üí Adds IP header

Data Link Layer ‚Üí Adds MAC header & Trailer

Physical Layer ‚Üí Sends bits/signals

Receiver Side ‚Äî Decapsulation
Bits ‚Üí Frame ‚Üí Packet ‚Üí Segment ‚Üí Data ‚Üí Delivered to application

5Ô∏è‚É£ Detailed Data Unit Progression
Layer	Data Unit	What is added
7,6,5 Application	Data	HTTP/TLS
4 Transport	Segment	TCP/UDP + Ports
3 Network	Packet	IP Header
2 Data Link	Frame	MAC Header + CRC
1 Physical	Bits	Voltages/Signals
6Ô∏è‚É£ MAC Address vs IP Address
MAC	IP
48-bit address	32-bit IPv4 / 128-bit IPv6
Assigned by manufacturer	Assigned by network/admin
Used within LAN	Used across networks
Data Link layer	Network layer
Example MAC: AA:BB:CC:11:22:33
Example IP: 192.168.1.10

7Ô∏è‚É£ ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)
Converts IP ‚Üí MAC

Example:
PC wants to send to 192.168.1.20:

Broadcast ARP request

Target replies with MAC

Communication begins

8Ô∏è‚É£ IP Addressing and Subnetting
IPv4 Structure
32 bits ‚Üí 4 octets
Example: 192.168.1.10

Subnet Mask
Example: /24 = 255.255.255.0
Network ID: 192.168.1.0
Host Range: .1 ‚Äì .254
Broadcast: .255

9Ô∏è‚É£ IP Classes
Already provided earlier; adding usage:

Class	Range	Hosts	Usage
A	1.0.0.0‚Äì126.0.0.0	16M	Large orgs
B	128.0.0.0‚Äì191.255.0.0	65K	Universities
C	192.0.0.0‚Äì223.255.255.0	254	Small networks
D	224.0.0.0‚Äì239	‚Äì	Multicast
E	240.0.0.0‚Äì255	‚Äì	R&D
üîü Network Devices (Full List & OSI Layer)
Device	OSI Layer	Function
Hub	1	Broadcasts all traffic
Repeater	1	Signal regeneration
NIC	1	Connects device to network
Switch	2	MAC-based forwarding
Bridge	2	Divides LAN
WAP	2	Wi-Fi extension
Router	3	Routes packets
L3 Switch	3	Switching + Routing
Firewall	3/4/7	Filters traffic
Gateway	All	Converts protocols
Load Balancer	4/7	Distributes traffic
Proxy	7	Caching, filtering
1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Network Topologies
Topology	Description	Pros	Cons
Bus	Single cable	Simple	Failure stops all
Star	Central switch	Reliable	Costly
Ring	Circular	Predictable	One break stops all
Mesh	Fully connected	Fault tolerant	Expensive
Hybrid	Mixture	Flexible	Complex
1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Types of Communication
Unicast ‚Üí one-to-one

Broadcast ‚Üí one-to-all

Multicast ‚Üí one-to-many (group)

Anycast ‚Üí nearest node receives

1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Routing (In Detail)
Routers decide best path.

Routing Types:
Static Routing

Dynamic Routing

Routing Protocols:
OSPF ‚Üí link-state

RIP ‚Üí distance vector

BGP ‚Üí internet-level routing

EIGRP (Cisco)

Routing Table Contains:
Destination network

Next-hop

Interface

Metric

Route source

1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Switching (In Detail)
Switch uses MAC address table.

Switching Types:
Store and Forward

Cut Through

Fragment Free

VLAN (Virtual LAN)
Used to separate networks logically.

Trunk ports carry multiple VLANs via 802.1Q tagging.

1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ NAT (Network Address Translation)
Converts private IP ‚Üí public IP

Types:
Static NAT

Dynamic NAT

PAT (Port Address Translation)

Used in home routers and cloud VPCs.

1Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol)
Assigns:

IP address

Subnet mask

Gateway

DNS

Process: DORA

Discover

Offer

Request

Acknowledge

1Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ DNS (Domain Name System)
Converts domain ‚Üí IP.

Steps:

Query ‚Üí Resolver

Root server

TLD server

Authoritative server

Returns IP

